            <p:rationale>Duplicative capability is expensive, increases an unwanted complexity of the information environment, and proliferates conflicting data and information.
The use of common solutions is favored wherever it is possible and feasible.</p:rationale>
            <p:implications>Particular organizations, which depend upon a capability that does not serve the entire enterprise, must change over to the enterprise-wide solution. Only in specific cases, when a specific capability cannot be provided by the enterprise-wide solution, can exceptions be allowed. These need to be documented, tracked over time, and if a sufficient capability is available in an enterprise-wide solution, they must be replaced. If there is no sufficient equivalent in an enterprise-wide solution, these exceptions can be adopted and enforced to become a part of the enterprise-wide solution.
The policies enforcing an adherence of these rules need to defined, documented and put in place. Any exception must be documented and tracked over time.
This mechanism will help to ensure that data and information supporting enterprise decision-making and business processes will be standardized and managed in the same manner. Data processing will use the same mechanisms across the entire enterprise.</p:implications>
